@node introduction "Introduction"

@{b}1 - Introduction@{ub}

   @{b}gtoh@{ub} is a little utility to convert guide files into html files.
   Each node of the original guide file is writen in an independant html file.
   The main node is written in the main.html file.

@endnode

@node config "System requirements"

@{b}2 - System requirements@{ub}

   2.1 - Hard

   Nothing special, except an @{"Amiga" link amiga} and a monitor ;-).

   2.2 - Soft

   You need at least Kickstart 2.04 and Workbench 2.04, and perhaps @{b}gtoh@{ub}.

@endnode

@node amiga "Amiga"

@{b}@{i}Amiga@{ub}@{ui}

   The best ever man-made machine...

@endnode

@node installation "Installation"

@{b}3 - Installation@{ub}

   Just copy the @{b}gtoh@{ub} executable somewhere in you path (c: or tools for example).
   Then, copy the guide file where you want.

@endnode

@node usage "Usage"

@{b}4 - Usage@{ub}

   4.1 - From a shell window

   To see @{b}gtoh@{ub}'s options, type 'gtoh ?' in a shell window.

   Options:

   -o     : indicates the full path name of the output directory.

   -a     : add a line on the main html page below wich the fields database, copyright, version and author
            are inserted if they were found in the original guide file.

   -w     : indicate your web address, to put it at the bottom of the main page.

   -m     : same as below but for your email address.

   -i     : indicates the full path name of a picture to put on background of each pages.

  - f     : indicates the guide file you want to convert.

   4.2 - From the Workbench

   Double-clic on @{b}gtoh@{ub}'s icon and fill in the string gadgets you want. The input file
   string gadget is the only one that is necessary to fill in order to convert a guide file.

   Clic on the [OK] button to start the conversion, and on the [Cancel] button or on the close
   window gadget to quit @{b}gtoh@{ub}.
    
@endnode

@node register "How to register?"

@{b}5 - How to register?@{ub}

   Since @{b}gtoh@{ub} is freeware there's no need to register, but you should
   simply send me an @{"email" link auteur} or a postcard.

@endnode

